{
  "doc_id": "59504",
  "text": "Echocardiographic screening is part of the evaluation of every patient presenting with hypotension, breathlessness, chest discomfort, and/or symptoms of low cardiac output after catheter ablation of AF. [CITATION_1] TTE screening for pericardial effusion after even uncomplicated catheter ablation of AF is performed in some labs. If a pericardiocentesis is performed, periodic TTE are performed to monitor response to, or to screen for re-accumulation of pericardial fluid and/or timing of re-starting anticoagulation. After discharge, a post-procedure Dressler-like syndrome, atrial tachycardia in the setting of LV dysfunction or volume overload, and diastolic atrial dysfunction (oedema after extensive atrial ablation) may all be part of the differential diagnosis of breathlessness and echocardiography has a key role in allowing the correct diagnosis and optimal treatment.",
